@lzybkr 
> I had feedback in the form of a PR to TabExpansionPlusPlus that caching should be built-in.

It feels almost more often than not that I implement some sort of custom completion caching. But often with less than stellar aging/expiration.

We can add an interface:

```c#
public interface IExtendedValidateArguments
{
    void Validate(object arguments, EngineIntrinsics engineIntrinsics, /* extra args*/);
}
```

Then:
```C#
    public abstract class ValidateArgumentsAttribute : CmdletMetadataAttribute
    {
        //...

        internal void InternalValidate(object o, EngineIntrinsics engineIntrinsics, /* extra args */)
        {
            if (var extended = this as IExtendedValidateArguments) {
                extended.Validate(o, engineIntrinsics, /* extra args */ );
            } else {
                Validate(o, engineIntrinsics);
            }
        }
```

And lastly implement that interface for ValidateSetAttribute.

Alternatively, we can move the type test to the parameter binder to avoid passing extra arguments if that is expensive somehow.
